## B

[Babinet's principle](/Babinet%27s_principle)
A theorem in diffraction theory stating that the diffraction pattern produced by an opaque object is identical to that produced by a hole of the same size and shape, except for the overall intensity of the forward beam. It's a rather elegant symmetry in wave behavior.

[background radiation](/Background_radiation)
The ubiquitous [ionizing radiation](/Ionizing_radiation) that permeates the environment and to which the general population is exposed. It's the universe's ambient hum.

balanced forces
When all the forces acting on an object cancel each other out, resulting in no net force. The object remains at rest or continues in uniform motion. It's equilibrium.

[ballistics](/Ballistics)
The science of the motion of projectiles, particularly bullets, rockets, and missiles. It’s the physics of flight, often with explosive beginnings.

[Balmer series](/Balmer_series)
A set of spectral lines emitted by [hydrogen atoms](/Hydrogen_atom) in the visible spectrum. Discovered by Johann Balmer, these lines are described by the Balmer formula and are a cornerstone of atomic spectroscopy.

[barometer](/Barometer)
An instrument used to measure [atmospheric pressure](/Atmospheric_pressure). Changes in pressure can often forecast short-term weather shifts.

[baryon](/Baryon)
A class of composite subatomic particles, such as protons and neutrons, made up of three quarks. Most of the ordinary matter we encounter is baryonic. They are a type of fermion.

[battery (electricity)](/Battery_(electricity))
A device that converts chemical energy into electrical energy, consisting of two or more connected electrical cells.

[beam](/Beam_(structure))
A structural element designed to resist loads primarily through bending. Found in buildings, bridges, and even machine frames, beams are fundamental to structural integrity.

[bending](/Bending)
Also known as flexure, this describes the behavior of a structural element, like a beam, when subjected to a load perpendicular to its longitudinal axis, causing it to deform.

[bending moment](/Bending_moment)
The internal reaction within a structural element caused by an external force or moment, leading to [bending](/Bending). Beams are particularly susceptible to bending moments.&#91;20&#93; &#91;21&#93;

[Bernoulli equation](/Bernoulli%27s_equation)
An equation describing the conservation of energy in fluid flow.

[Bernoulli's principle](/Bernoulli%27s_principle)
In [fluid dynamics](/Fluid_dynamics), this principle states that an increase in the speed of a fluid is accompanied by a decrease in pressure or a decrease in the fluid's potential energy. It explains phenomena from airplane lift to why a shower curtain billows inward.&#91;22&#93; &#58;&#8202;Ch.3&#8202; &#91;23&#93; &#58;&#8202;156–164,&#8202;§ 3.5&#8202;

[Bessel function](/Bessel_function)
A solution to [Friedrich Bessel](/Friedrich_Bessel)'s differential equation, these functions are crucial in solving problems involving wave propagation and potential theory, particularly in [cylindrical coordinates](/Cylindrical_coordinates) and [spherical coordinates](/Spherical_coordinates).&#91;25&#93;

[beta decay](/Beta_decay)
Also denoted as β-decay, this is a type of radioactive decay in which an atomic nucleus emits a beta particle (an electron or positron), transforming into a different nuclide.

[beta particle](/Beta_particle)
A high-energy, high-speed electron or positron emitted from the nucleus of a radioactive atom during [beta decay](/Beta_decay).

[Big Bang](/Big_Bang)
The prevailing cosmological model that describes the origin and early evolution of the [Universe](/Universe). It posits that the universe began in an extremely hot, dense state and has been expanding and cooling ever since.

[binding energy](/Binding_energy)
The energy required to disassemble a system into its constituent parts. For bound systems, this energy is negative, indicating that the combined entity has lower energy than its separate components.

[binomial random variable](/Binomial_random_variable)
A random variable that describes the number of successes in a fixed number of independent Bernoulli trials.

[biocatalysis](/Biocatalysis)
The process of accelerating a chemical reaction using biological catalysts, such as enzymes.

[biophysics](/Biophysics)
An interdisciplinary field that applies the principles and methods of [physics](/Physics) to the study of [biological](/Biology) systems. It seeks to understand life at its most fundamental physical level.

[black body](/Black_body)
An idealized object that absorbs all incident [electromagnetic radiation](/Electromagnetic_radiation) without reflection. It's a theoretical construct used in thermodynamics to study radiation emission.

[black-body radiation](/Black-body_radiation)
The electromagnetic radiation emitted by a [black body](/Black_body) in thermal equilibrium with its surroundings. Its spectrum is solely dependent on the temperature of the body, a fundamental concept in quantum physics.

[block and tackle](/Block_and_tackle)
A system of pulleys and ropes used to lift or pull heavy loads by multiplying force. A classic example of mechanical advantage.

[Bohr model](/Bohr_model)
An early model of the atom that proposed electrons orbit the nucleus in specific energy levels. While superseded, it was a crucial step in understanding atomic structure.

[boiling point](/Boiling_point)
The temperature at which the vapor pressure of a liquid equals the ambient pressure, causing it to transition into a gas.

[boiling point elevation](/Boiling_point_elevation)
The phenomenon where the [boiling point](/Boiling_point) of a liquid solvent increases when a non-volatile solute is dissolved in it. The resulting solution has a higher boiling point than the pure solvent.

[Boltzmann constant](/Boltzmann_constant)
A fundamental physical constant that relates the average kinetic energy of particles in a gas to the [temperature](/Temperature) of the gas. It's a bridge between the microscopic and macroscopic worlds.

[Bose–Einstein condensate](/Bose%E2%80%93Einstein_condensate) (BEC)
A state of matter formed by cooling a gas of bosons to near [absolute zero](/Absolute_zero), where a large fraction of the bosons occupy the lowest quantum state, behaving like a single quantum entity.

[boson](/Boson)
A type of subatomic particle that follows [Bose–Einstein statistics](/Bose%E2%80%93Einstein_statistics) and has integer [spin](/Spin_quantum_number). Examples include photons, gluons, and the Higgs boson. Unlike fermions, multiple bosons can occupy the same quantum state.

[Boyle's law](/Boyle%27s_law)
A gas law stating that at constant temperature, the volume of a fixed mass of gas is inversely proportional to its pressure.

[Bra–ket notation](/Bra%E2%80%93ket_notation)
A standard notation in [quantum mechanics](/Quantum_mechanics) for representing quantum states and operators.

[Bragg's law](/Bragg%27s_law)
A law describing the diffraction of X-rays by crystals, relating the wavelength of the X-rays, the spacing between crystal planes, and the angle of diffraction.

[bremsstrahlung](/Bremsstrahlung)
Radiation produced when a charged particle is decelerated as it passes through matter. It's often seen in X-ray tubes.

[Brewster's angle](/Brewster%27s_angle)
Also known as the polarization angle, this is the specific angle of incidence at which light with a particular polarization is completely transmitted through a transparent dielectric surface without reflection. Unpolarized light incident at this angle will be reflected in a perfectly polarized state.

[british thermal unit](/British_thermal_unit) (btu)
An older unit of energy, defined as the amount of heat required to raise the temperature of one pound of water by one degree Fahrenheit. Largely replaced by the [joule](/Joule) in scientific contexts.

[brittleness](/Brittleness)
The tendency of a material to fracture with little or no plastic deformation when subjected to stress. Brittle materials absorb less energy before breaking.

[Brownian motion](/Brownian_motion)
The random movement of particles suspended in a fluid (liquid or gas) resulting from their continuous bombardment by the molecules of the fluid. It provides compelling evidence for the existence of atoms and molecules.

[bubble](/Bubble_(physics))
A globule of gas enclosed within a liquid or solid.

[Bulk modulus](/Bulk_modulus)
A measure of a substance's resistance to uniform compression. It is defined as the ratio of the applied pressure to the resulting fractional decrease in volume. Its SI unit is the pascal.

[buoyancy](/Buoyancy)
The upward force exerted by a fluid that opposes the weight of an immersed object. It's why things float.

---

## C

[calculus](/Calculus)
A fundamental branch of [mathematics](/Mathematics) dealing with change. It comprises [differential calculus](/Differential_calculus), which studies rates of change and slopes, and [integral calculus](/Integral_calculus), which deals with accumulation and areas. These two are linked by the [fundamental theorem of calculus](/Fundamental_theorem_of_calculus).

[capacitance](/Capacitance)
The ability of a system to store electric charge. It's defined as the ratio of the change in electric charge to the corresponding change in electric potential. The SI unit is the [farad](/Farad).

[capacitive reactance](/Capacitive_reactance)
The opposition offered by a capacitor to the flow of alternating current, which is inversely proportional to the frequency and capacitance.&#91;24&#93;

[capacitor](/Capacitor)
An electrical component consisting of two conductive plates separated by an insulating dielectric material, used to store electrical energy in an electric field.

[Carnot cycle](/Carnot_cycle)
A theoretical thermodynamic cycle that sets the maximum possible efficiency for converting heat into work. It’s an idealization used to understand the limits of heat engines.

[Cartesian coordinate system](/Cartesian_coordinate_system)
A coordinate system that defines each point in space by its signed distances from a set of mutually perpendicular axes. It's the familiar (x, y, z) system.

[cathode](/Cathode)
The electrode through which conventional electric current flows out of a polarized electrical device. In a [galvanic cell](/Galvanic_cell), it's the positive terminal; in an electrolytic cell, it's the negative one. It's where reduction occurs. Contrast with [anode](/Anode).

[cathode ray](/Cathode_ray)
A beam of electrons emitted from the negative electrode (cathode) in a vacuum tube.

[cation](/Cation)
An ion carrying a net positive electric charge. The opposite of an [anion](/Anion).

[celestial mechanics](/Celestial_mechanics)
The branch of [astronomy](/Astronomy) and [physics](/Physics) that deals with the motion of celestial bodies, governed by the laws of [gravitation](/Gravitation).

[Celsius scale](/Celsius_scale)
Also known as the centigrade scale, this is a widely used scale for measuring [temperature](/Temperature). Water freezes at 0°C and boils at 100°C at standard atmospheric pressure.

[center of curvature](/Center_of_curvature)
The center of the sphere or circle of which an arc or surface is a part.

[center of gravity](/Center_of_gravity)
The point in a body where the force of gravity can be considered to act. For uniform gravitational fields, it coincides with the [center of mass](/Center_of_mass).

[center of mass](/Center_of_mass)
The unique point in space representing the average position of all the mass in a system. It's the point where an object would balance.

[center of pressure](/Center_of_pressure_(fluid_mechanics))
The point on a submerged surface where the resultant hydrostatic force acts.

[centigrade](/Centigrade_(temperature))
See [Celsius scale](/Celsius_scale).

[central-force problem](/Classical_central-force_problem)
A classic problem in [potential theory](/Potential_theory) describing the motion of a particle under the influence of a force directed towards a fixed center. Gravity and electromagnetism are examples of central forces.

[centrifugal force](/Centrifugal_force)
An apparent outward force experienced by an object moving in a curved path. It's a consequence of inertia, often described as a fictitious force in a rotating frame of reference.

[centripetal force](/Centripetal_force)
A real force directed towards the center of a circular path, necessary to keep an object moving in that path. Without it, the object would move in a straight line due to inertia.

[cGh physics](/CGh_physics)
A hypothetical framework in [theoretical physics](/Theoretical_physics) aiming to unify relativity, gravitation, and quantum mechanics by considering the fundamental constants [speed of light](/Speed_of_light) (c), the [gravitational constant](/Gravitational_constant) (G), and [Planck constant](/Planck_constant) (h) as dimensions. The realm where all three constants are simultaneously significant, [quantum gravity](/Quantum_gravity), remains the most challenging corner.

[chain reaction](/Chain_reaction)
A self-sustaining series of reactions where a product of one reaction triggers subsequent similar reactions. Most notably seen in nuclear fission.

[change of base rule](/Change_of_base_rule)
A rule in [logarithms](/Logarithm) that allows conversion between different bases.

[charge carrier](/Charge_carrier)
A mobile entity carrying an electric charge, such as an electron or ion, responsible for electric current.

[chemical physics](/Chemical_physics)
An interdisciplinary field that applies the principles of [physics](/Physics) to study chemical phenomena and processes.

[chromatic aberration](/Chromatic_aberration)
An optical distortion where a lens fails to focus all colors of light to the same point, resulting in color fringing.

[circular motion](/Circular_motion)
Motion along the path of a circle.

[classical mechanics](/Classical_mechanics)
Also known as Newtonian mechanics, this is the branch of [physics](/Physics) that describes the motion of macroscopic objects under the influence of forces, based on [Newton's laws of motion](/Newton%27s_laws_of_motion).

[coefficient of friction](/Friction)
A dimensionless quantity representing the ratio of the force of friction between two bodies and the normal force pressing them together.

[coherence](/Coherence_(physics))
A property of waves where their phase relationship is constant over time and space. Lasers produce highly coherent light.

[cohesion](/Cohesion_(chemistry))
The tendency of similar particles or surfaces to cling to one another. It's the force that holds molecules of the same substance together, contrasting with [adhesion](/Adhesion).

[cold fusion](/Cold_fusion)
A hypothesized type of nuclear reaction that would occur at or near room temperature, unlike conventional fusion which requires extremely high temperatures. It remains a controversial and unproven phenomenon.

[complex harmonic motion](/Complex_harmonic_motion)
The superposition of two or more simple harmonic motions, resulting in more intricate oscillatory patterns.

[composite particle](/Composite_particle)
A particle made up of two or more smaller particles, such as protons and neutrons (which are made of quarks).

[Compton scattering](/Compton_scattering)
The scattering of a [photon](/Photon) by a charged particle, typically an electron, resulting in a decrease in the photon's energy (and an increase in wavelength) and the acceleration of the electron. The opposite is inverse Compton scattering.

[concave lens](/Concave_lens)
A lens that is thinner in the middle than at the edges, causing parallel light rays to diverge.

[condensation point](/Condensation_point)
The temperature at which a gas or vapor turns into a liquid. It's the same as the [boiling point](/Boiling_point) at a given pressure.

[condensed matter physics](/Condensed_matter_physics)
A major branch of [physics](/Physics) that studies the macroscopic and microscopic physical properties of matter, particularly the solid and liquid phases.

[conservation of momentum](/Momentum)
A fundamental principle stating that the total momentum of a closed system remains constant over time.

[conservation law](/Conservation_law)
A principle stating that a particular quantity (e.g., energy, momentum) remains constant in an isolated physical system.

[constructive interference](/Constructive_interference)
The superposition of two or more waves that results in a wave of increased amplitude. This occurs when wave crests align with crests and troughs with troughs.

[continuous spectrum](/Continuous_spectrum)
A spectrum in which there are no gaps, containing radiation over a range of wavelengths. Stars emit continuous spectra.

[continuum mechanics](/Continuum_mechanics)
A branch of [mechanics](/Mechanics) that treats matter as a continuous medium rather than as discrete atoms or molecules. It's used to study the behavior of [fluids](/Fluid) and [solids](/Solid).

[convection](/Convection)
The transfer of heat through the movement of fluids (liquids or gases). Hotter, less dense fluid rises, while cooler, denser fluid sinks, creating a circulation.

[convex lens](/Convex_lens)
A lens that is thicker in the middle than at the edges, causing parallel light rays to converge.

[coulomb](/Coulomb) (C)
The SI derived unit of electric charge. It's defined as the charge transported by a constant current of one [ampere](/Ampere) in one second.

[Coulomb's law](/Coulomb%27s_law)
The fundamental law describing the electrostatic force between two point charges, stating that the force is directly proportional to the product of the charges and inversely proportional to the square of the distance between them.

[converging lens](/Lens_(optics))
See [convex lens](/Convex_lens).

[cosmic background radiation](/Cosmic_background_radiation)
The faint [electromagnetic radiation](/Electromagnetic_radiation) filling the universe, considered a remnant of the [Big Bang](/Big_Bang).

[creep](/Creep_(deformation))
The tendency of a solid material to move slowly or deform permanently under the influence of persistent mechanical stresses. It's often observed at high temperatures.

[crest](/Crest_(physics))
The highest point of a wave cycle.

[crest factor](/Crest_factor)
The ratio of the peak value of a waveform to its root mean square (RMS) value.

[critical angle](/Critical_angle_(optics))
The angle of incidence above which a ray of light striking an interface between two media is totally internally reflected.

[critical mass](/Critical_mass)
The minimum amount of fissile material required to sustain a nuclear chain reaction.

[cube of theoretical physics](/CGh_physics)
See [cGh physics](/CGh_physics).

[Curie temperature](/Curie_temperature)
The temperature above which a ferromagnetic material loses its permanent magnetism and becomes paramagnetic.

[current density](/Current_density)
The electric current per unit area, flowing perpendicular to the current.

current length
This seems to be a placeholder or a term not commonly used in standard physics. It might refer to the instantaneous length of a conductor carrying current, but without further context, its meaning is ambiguous.

[curvilinear motion](/Curvilinear_motion)
Motion along a curved path. Both planar and cylindrical coordinate systems are used to describe it.

[cyclotron](/Cyclotron)
A type of particle accelerator that uses a magnetic field to accelerate [charged particles](/Charged_particles) outwards from the center along a spiral path.

---

## D

[Dalton's law](/Dalton%27s_law)
Specifically, Dalton's law of partial pressures states that the total pressure exerted by a mixture of gases is equal to the sum of the partial pressures of the individual gases.

[damped vibration](/Damped_vibration)
Oscillations that decrease in amplitude over time due to energy dissipation, often caused by friction or resistance.

[Damping ratio](/Damping_ratio)
A measure of how oscillations in a system decay after a disturbance. A high damping ratio means oscillations die out quickly.

[Darcy–Weisbach equation](/Darcy%E2%80%93Weisbach_equation)
An empirical equation used in [fluid mechanics](/Fluid_mechanics) to calculate the pressure drop of a fluid in a pipe.

[dark energy](/Dark_energy)
A mysterious form of energy hypothesized to permeate all of space and drive the [accelerating expansion of the universe](/Accelerating_expansion_of_the_universe). Its nature remains one of the biggest puzzles in cosmology.

[dark matter](/Dark_matter)
A hypothetical form of matter that does not interact with light or other [electromagnetic radiation](/Electromagnetic_radiation), making it invisible. Its existence is inferred from its gravitational effects on visible matter.

[DC motor](/DC_motor)
An electric motor that runs on [direct current](/Direct_current) (DC) power.

[decibel](/Decibel) (dB)
A logarithmic unit used to express the ratio of two values of a physical quantity, commonly used for sound intensity or signal power.

[definite integral](/Definite_integral)
An integral that yields a numerical value, representing the net area under a curve between two specified limits.

[deflection](/Deflection_(engineering))
The displacement or bending of a structural element under load. It can be measured as an angle or a distance.

[deformation](/Deformation_(mechanics))
The change in shape or size of a body due to applied forces or stresses.

[density](/Density)
Also known as mass density, this is a fundamental physical property of a substance, defined as its mass per unit volume. It tells you how much "stuff" is packed into a given space.

[derivative](/Derivative)
In calculus, the derivative measures the instantaneous rate of change of a function with respect to its variable. It's the slope of the tangent line at any point on a curve, fundamentally describing how things change.

[destructive interference](/Destructive_interference)
The superposition of two or more waves that results in a wave of reduced amplitude, often canceling each other out. This happens when wave crests align with troughs.

[diamagnetism](/Diamagnetism)
A property of materials that are weakly repelled by an external magnetic field. All materials exhibit diamagnetism to some extent.

[dielectric](/Dielectric)
An electrical insulator that can be polarized by an applied electric field. When placed in an electric field, charges within the dielectric shift slightly, creating an opposing internal field.

[diffraction](/Diffraction)
The phenomenon where waves bend and spread out as they pass through an opening or around an obstacle. It's a key characteristic of wave behavior.

[direct current](/Direct_current) (DC)
Electric current that flows in only one direction. Batteries provide DC power. Contrast with [alternating current](/Alternating_current) (AC).

[dispersion](/Dispersion_(optics))
The phenomenon where the speed of light in a medium depends on its wavelength, causing different colors to refract at slightly different angles. This is responsible for prisms splitting white light into a spectrum.

[displacement](/Displacement_(vector))
A vector quantity representing the shortest distance from an object's initial position to its final position. It indicates both distance and direction, unlike scalar distance.

[distance](/Distance)
A numerical measure of how far apart two points or objects are. It's a scalar quantity.

[drift velocity](/Drift_velocity)
The average velocity attained by charged particles (like electrons in a conductor) in a material due to an electric field. It's typically much slower than the random thermal motion of the particles.

[Doppler effect](/Doppler_effect)
The change in frequency (and wavelength) of a wave in relation to an observer who is moving relative to the wave source. This is why the pitch of a siren changes as it passes.

[drag](/Drag_(physics))
A resistive force exerted by a fluid (liquid or gas) on an object moving through it, acting in the direction opposite to the object's motion. It depends on velocity, shape, and fluid properties.

[ductility](/Ductility)
The ability of a solid material to deform under tensile stress without fracturing, often characterized by its ability to be drawn into a wire.

[dynamics](/Dynamics_(mechanics))
The branch of classical mechanics that studies forces and torques and their influence on motion, as opposed to [kinematics](/Kinematics), which describes motion itself.

[dyne](/Dyne)
A unit of force in the [cgs](/Cgs_(unit_system)) system, equal to the force required to accelerate a mass of one gram by one centimetre per second squared. It's an older unit, largely superseded by the [newton](/Newton_(unit)).

---

## E

[econophysics](/Econophysics)
An interdisciplinary field that applies the methods of [physics](/Physics) to the study of economics.

[elastic collision](/Elastic_collision)
A collision in which both [momentum](/Momentum) and [kinetic energy](/Kinetic_energy) are conserved. Particles bounce off each other perfectly.

[elastic energy](/Elastic_energy)
Potential energy stored in a material when it is deformed elastically.

[elastic instability](/Elastic_instability)
A phenomenon where a structure loses its stability and undergoes large deformations under load, even if the stress remains below the material's yield strength.

[elastic modulus](/Elastic_modulus)
A measure of a material's stiffness or resistance to elastic deformation. It relates stress to strain.

[elasticity](/Elasticity_(physics))
The property of a material that allows it to return to its original shape and size after being deformed.

[electric charge](/Electric_charge)
A fundamental property of matter that causes it to experience a force when placed in an electric or magnetic field. It exists in positive and negative forms.

[electric circuit](/Electric_circuit)
A closed path through which electric current can flow, consisting of electrical components and a power source.

[electric current](/Electric_current)
The flow of electric charge through a conductor. Measured in [amperes](/Ampere).

[electric displacement field](/Electric_displacement_field)
A vector field used in [electromagnetism](/Electromagnetism) that relates to the electric field and the polarization of a dielectric medium.

[electric field](/Electric_field)
A region of space around an electric charge or a changing magnetic field where electric forces can be detected. It exerts a force on other charges.

[electric field gradient](/Electric_field_gradient)
The rate of change of the electric field with respect to position.

[electric field intensity](/Electric_intensity)
See [electric field](/Electric_field).

[electric generator](/Electric_generator)
A device that converts mechanical energy into electrical energy, typically through electromagnetic induction.

[electric motor](/Electric_motor)
A device that converts electrical energy into mechanical energy, using the interaction between magnetic fields and electric currents.

[electric potential](/Electric_potential)
The amount of work needed per unit charge to move a charge from a reference point to a specific point in an electric field. Measured in [volts](/Volt).

[electric power](/Electric_power)
The rate at which electrical energy is transferred or consumed. Measured in [watts](/Watt).

[electrical conductor](/Electrical_conductor)
A material that allows electric charge to flow freely through it, such as metals.

[electrical insulator](/Electrical_insulator)
A material that strongly resists the flow of electric charge, such as rubber or glass.

[electrical potential energy](/Electrical_potential_energy)
The potential energy a charged object possesses due to its position in an electric field.

[electrical and electronics engineering](/Electrical_and_electronics_engineering)
An engineering discipline that deals with electricity, electronics, and electromagnetism.

[electrical network](/Electrical_network)
A system of interconnected electrical components.

[electrical resistance](/Electrical_resistance)
The opposition to the flow of electric current in a material or component. Measured in [ohms](/Ohm).

[electricity](/Electricity)
The phenomenon associated with the presence and flow of electric charge.

[electro-optic effect](/Electro-optic_effect)
Changes in the optical properties of a material in response to an applied electric field.

[electrochemical cell](/Electrochemical_cell)
A device that generates electric current from chemical reactions or uses electricity to drive chemical reactions.

[electrodynamics](/Electrodynamics)
The branch of physics that studies electric charges and currents and their interaction with electric and magnetic fields.

[electrolytic cell](/Electrolytic_cell)
An electrochemical cell that uses electrical energy to drive a non-spontaneous chemical reaction.

[electromagnet](/Electromagnet)
A magnet whose magnetic field is produced by an electric current. The magnetism disappears when the current is turned off.

[electromagnetic field](/Electromagnetic_field)
A field that permeates space, consisting of electric and magnetic fields, generated by charged objects and varying currents. It mediates the electromagnetic force.

[electromagnetic induction](/Electromagnetic_induction)
The production of an electromotive force (voltage) across an electrical conductor in a changing magnetic field. This is the principle behind electric generators.

[electromagnetic radiation](/Electromagnetic_radiation)
Energy that travels and spreads in the form of waves, including radio waves, microwaves, infrared, visible light, ultraviolet, X-rays, and gamma rays.

[electromagnetic spectrum](/Electromagnetic_spectrum)
The entire range of electromagnetic radiation, ordered by frequency or wavelength.

[electromagnetic wave equation](/Electromagnetic_wave_equation)
A set of equations that describe the propagation of electromagnetic waves.

[electromagnetism](/Electromagnetism)
The branch of physics that studies the phenomena associated with electric charges and currents, and their interactions with electric and magnetic fields.

[electromechanics](/Electromechanics)
The study and application of the interplay between electrical and mechanical systems.

[electromotive force](/Electromotive_force) (emf or E)
The energy per unit charge supplied by a source of electrical energy, such as a battery or generator. It's the "electrical pressure" that drives current. Measured in [volts](/Volt).

[electron](/Electron)
A fundamental subatomic particle with a negative electric charge and a very small mass. Electrons orbit the atomic nucleus and are responsible for chemical bonding and electric current.

[electron capture](/Electron_capture)
A type of radioactive decay in which an atomic nucleus absorbs an electron, converting a proton into a neutron and emitting a neutrino.

[electron cloud](/Atomic_orbital)
The region around an atomic nucleus where electrons are likely to be found, described by [atomic orbitals](/Atomic_orbital).

[electron pair](/Electron_pair)
Two electrons, often with opposite spins, that are bound together.

[electron paramagnetic resonance](/Electron_paramagnetic_resonance)
Also known as electron spin resonance (ESR), this is a spectroscopic technique used to study materials with unpaired electrons, exploiting the [Zeeman effect](/Zeeman_effect).

[electronvolt](/Electronvolt) (eV)
A unit of energy commonly used in particle physics, equal to the energy gained by an electron moving through an electric potential difference of one volt. Approximately 1.6×10⁻¹⁹ joules.

[electronegativity](/Electronegativity)
A measure of the tendency of an atom or molecule to attract electrons or electron density towards itself in a chemical bond.

[electronics](/Electronics)
The branch of physics and engineering that deals with the behavior and control of electrons, particularly in circuits containing active components like transistors and diodes.

[electrostatics](/Electrostatics)
The study of stationary electric charges and the forces and fields they produce.

[electrostriction](/Electrostriction)
The phenomenon where a dielectric material deforms in response to an applied electric field, regardless of the field's polarity.

[elementary charge](/Elementary_charge) (e)
The magnitude of the charge of a single proton or electron, approximately 1.602 × 10⁻¹⁹ coulombs.

[elementary particle](/Elementary_particle)
A particle that cannot be subdivided into smaller particles. Examples include quarks, leptons, and bosons.

[emission spectrum](/Emission_spectrum)
A spectrum showing discrete lines of specific wavelengths emitted by excited atoms or molecules as they return to a lower energy state.

[emissivity](/Emissivity)
A measure of how effectively a surface emits thermal radiation, expressed as a fraction of the radiation emitted by a perfect [black body](/Black_body) at the same temperature.

[energy](/Energy)
The capacity to do work. It exists in various forms, such as kinetic, potential, thermal, and electromagnetic.

[energy level](/Energy_level)
Specific discrete values of energy that a quantum system, such as an atom or molecule, can possess.

[endothermic](/Endothermic)
Describes a process or reaction that absorbs energy from its surroundings, usually in the form of heat. Contrast with [exothermic](/Exothermic).

[engineering physics](/Engineering_physics)
An interdisciplinary field that combines principles of physics with engineering applications, often focusing on advanced technologies and materials.

[enthalpy](/Enthalpy)
A thermodynamic property representing the total heat content of a system. It is the sum of the internal energy and the product of pressure and volume.

[entropy](/Entropy)
A measure of the disorder or randomness in a system. According to the [second law of thermodynamics](/Second_law_of_thermodynamics), the entropy of an isolated system tends to increase over time.

[equilibrant force](/Equilibrant_force)
A force that balances a system of other forces, bringing it into equilibrium.

[equipartition](/Equipartition)
In statistical mechanics, the principle that energy is distributed equally among all possible degrees of freedom of a system in thermal equilibrium.

[escape velocity](/Escape_velocity)
The minimum speed an object must achieve to overcome the gravitational pull of a celestial body and escape into space without further propulsion.

[excited state](/Excited_state)
A state of an atom, molecule, or nucleus in which its energy is higher than its ground state.

[exothermic](/Exothermic)
Describes a process or reaction that releases energy into its surroundings, usually in the form of heat. Contrast with [endothermic](/Endothermic).

[experimental physics](/Experimental_physics)
The branch of physics that relies on observation and experimentation to test theories and discover new phenomena.

---

## F

[farad](/Farad) (F)
The SI derived unit of electrical capacitance. One farad is the capacitance of a capacitor across which a potential difference of one volt results in a stored charge of one coulomb.

[falling bodies](/Falling_bodies)
Objects moving under the influence of gravity, typically towards a larger celestial body.

[faraday](/Faraday_(unit))
A unit of electric charge, equal to the charge of one mole of electrons.

[Faraday constant](/Faraday_constant)
The magnitude of the electric charge per mole of electrons, approximately 96,485 coulombs per mole.

[Fermat's principle](/Fermat%27s_principle)
A principle in optics stating that light travels between two points along the path that requires the least time. This leads to the laws of reflection and refraction.

[Fermi surface](/Fermi_surface)
In solid-state physics, a surface in reciprocal space separating occupied electron states from unoccupied states at absolute zero temperature.

[fermion](/Fermion)
A type of subatomic particle that obeys [Fermi–Dirac statistics](/Fermi%E2%80%93Dirac_statistics) and the [Pauli exclusion principle](/Pauli_exclusion_principle), meaning no two identical fermions can occupy the same quantum state. Examples include electrons, protons, and neutrons.

[ferrimagnetism](/Ferrimagnetism)
A type of magnetism similar to ferromagnetism, but where the magnetic moments of neighboring atoms are aligned in opposite directions with unequal magnitudes, resulting in a net magnetic moment.

[ferromagnetism](/Ferromagnetism)
A property of materials, like iron, that exhibit a strong attraction to magnets and can be magnetized themselves. They possess spontaneous magnetic ordering below a certain temperature (the Curie temperature).

[field line](/Field_line)
A graphical representation of a vector field, such as an electric or magnetic field. The lines indicate the direction and strength of the field.

[first law of thermodynamics](/First_law_of_thermodynamics)
The principle of conservation of energy applied to thermodynamic systems. It states that the change in internal energy of a system is equal to the heat added to the system minus the work done by the system.

[fission](/Nuclear_fission)
A nuclear reaction in which an atomic nucleus splits into two or more smaller nuclei, releasing a large amount of energy and neutrons.

[flavour](/Flavour_(particle_physics))
A property of quarks and leptons, analogous to electric charge, that distinguishes different types of these particles. There are six flavors of quarks (up, down, charm, strange, top, bottom) and six flavors of leptons (electron, muon, tau, and their corresponding neutrinos).

[fluid](/Fluid)
A substance that can flow and take the shape of its container, exhibiting no resistance to shear stress. Liquids and gases are fluids.

[fluid mechanics](/Fluid_mechanics)
The branch of [mechanics](/Mechanics) that studies the behavior of [fluids](/Fluid) (liquids, gases, and plasmas) at rest ([fluid statics](/Fluid_statics)) and in motion ([fluid dynamics](/Fluid_dynamics)).

[fluid physics](/Fluid_physics)
A broad term encompassing the study of the physical properties and behavior of fluids.

[fluid statics](/Fluid_statics)
The branch of [fluid mechanics](/Fluid_mechanics) concerned with fluids at rest. It deals with concepts like pressure and buoyancy.

[fluorescence](/Fluorescence)
A type of photoluminescence where a substance absorbs light at one wavelength and emits it at a longer wavelength almost instantaneously.

[flux](/Flux)
A measure of the flow of a substance or property through a surface. In physics, it often refers to the rate of flow of energy or particles.

[flux density](/Flux)
The amount of flux passing through a unit area. For magnetic fields, this is magnetic flux density, measured in [teslas](/Tesla_(unit)).

[focal length](/Focal_length)
The distance from the center of a lens or mirror to its focal point, where parallel rays of light converge or appear to diverge from.

[focus](/Focus_(optics))
The point at which parallel rays of light converge after passing through a lens or reflecting off a mirror.

[force](/Force) (F)
An interaction that, when unopposed, will change the motion of an object. It has both magnitude and direction, making it a vector quantity. Measured in [newtons](/Newton_(unit)).

[force carrier](/Force_carrier)
A fundamental particle (like a photon or gluon) that mediates one of the fundamental forces of nature.

[force field](/Force_field_(physics))
A region in space where a force can be detected, characterized by a vector at each point indicating the force's magnitude and direction.

[frame of reference](/Frame_of_reference)
A coordinate system used to describe the position and motion of objects. The laws of physics are the same in all inertial frames of reference.

[Fraunhofer lines](/Fraunhofer_lines)
Dark lines in the solar spectrum that correspond to specific wavelengths of light absorbed by elements in the Sun's atmosphere.

[free body diagram](/Free_body_diagram)
A diagram used in physics to illustrate all the forces acting on an object.

[frequency](/Frequency)
The number of cycles or oscillations of a wave or periodic phenomenon per unit time. Measured in [hertz](/Hertz).

[frequency modulation](/Frequency_modulation) (FM)
A method of encoding information in a carrier wave by varying its frequency.

[free fall](/Free_fall)
Motion under the sole influence of gravity. An object in free fall experiences weightlessness.

[freezing point](/Freezing_point)
The temperature at which a substance transitions from a liquid to a solid state.

[friction](/Friction)
A force that opposes motion between surfaces in contact. It can be static (preventing motion) or kinetic (resisting motion).

[function](/Function_(mathematics))
A relation between a set of inputs and a set of permissible outputs with the property that each input is related to exactly one output.

[fundamental forces](/Fundamental_forces)
The four basic interactions in nature: strong nuclear, weak nuclear, electromagnetic, and gravitational. Also known as fundamental interactions.

[fundamental frequency](/Fundamental_frequency)
The lowest frequency of a periodic waveform, which determines the fundamental pitch of a sound.

[fundamental theorem of calculus](/Fundamental_theorem_of_calculus)
A theorem linking differential and integral calculus, stating that differentiation and integration are inverse operations.

[fusion](/Nuclear_fusion)
A nuclear reaction in which two or more atomic nuclei combine to form a heavier nucleus, releasing immense amounts of energy. This is the power source of stars.

---

## G

[gamma ray](/Gamma_ray)
A high-energy form of electromagnetic radiation, typically produced by radioactive decay or nuclear reactions. They have very short wavelengths and high penetrating power.

[gas](/Gas)
One of the states of matter, characterized by having no fixed shape or volume, and consisting of particles that move randomly and rapidly.

[general relativity](/General_relativity)
Einstein's theory of gravitation, which describes gravity not as a force, but as a curvature of spacetime caused by mass and energy.

[geophysics](/Geophysics)
The branch of [Earth science](/Earth_science) that applies the principles of [physics](/Physics) to study the Earth and its atmosphere.

[gluon](/Gluon)
The elementary particle that mediates the [strong interaction](/Strong_interaction), binding quarks together to form protons and neutrons.

[Graham's law of diffusion](/Graham%27s_law_of_diffusion)
States that the rate of diffusion or effusion of a gas is inversely proportional to the square root of its molar mass.

[gravitation](/Gravitation)
Also known as gravity, this is the fundamental force of attraction between any two objects with mass. It governs the motion of planets, stars, and galaxies.

[gravitational constant](/Gravitational_constant) (G)
A fundamental physical constant that appears in Newton's law of universal gravitation and Einstein's field equations. It determines the strength of the gravitational force.

[gravitational energy](/Gravitational_energy)
The potential energy an object possesses due to its position in a gravitational field.

[gravitational field](/Gravitational_field)
A region of space around a massive body where gravitational forces can be detected. It's often visualized using [field lines](/Field_line).

[gravitational potential](/Gravitational_potential)
The work done per unit mass to move an object from a reference point to a specific point in a gravitational field.

[gravitational wave](/Gravitational_wave)
Ripples in the fabric of spacetime, predicted by [general relativity](/General_relativity), caused by accelerating massive objects. Their detection confirmed a major prediction of Einstein's theory.

[graviton](/Graviton)
A hypothetical elementary particle that mediates the force of [gravitation](/Gravitation). It is predicted to be massless and travel at the speed of light.

[gravity](/Gravity)
See [gravitation](/Gravitation).

[ground](/Ground_(electricity))
A common reference point in an electrical circuit, typically set to zero potential.

[ground reaction force](/Ground_reaction_force)
The force exerted by the ground on an object in contact with it, equal and opposite to the force exerted by the object on the ground (Newton's third law).

[ground state](/Ground_state)
The lowest possible energy state of a quantum mechanical system, such as an atom or molecule.

[group velocity](/Group_velocity)
The velocity at which the envelope of a wave packet, representing the overall shape of the wave, propagates.

---

## H

[hadron](/Hadron)
A composite particle made of quarks and/or antiquarks, held together by the [strong interaction](/Strong_interaction). Protons and neutrons are examples of hadrons.

[half-life](/Half-life)
The time required for half of a sample of a radioactive substance to undergo decay. It's a measure of radioactive decay rate.

[Hamilton's principle](/Hamilton%27s_principle)
A fundamental principle in classical mechanics stating that the path taken by a physical system between two points in time is the one that minimizes the action.

[Hamiltonian mechanics](/Hamiltonian_mechanics)
A reformulation of classical mechanics that uses generalized coordinates and momenta, providing a more abstract and powerful framework.

[harmonic mean](/Harmonic_mean)
A type of average, calculated as the reciprocal of the arithmetic mean of the reciprocals of the numbers.

[heat](/Heat)
Energy transferred between systems due to a temperature difference. It flows from hotter to colder objects.

[heat transfer](/Heat_transfer)
The study of the mechanisms by which thermal energy is exchanged between physical systems. The primary modes are conduction, convection, and radiation.

[Helmholtz free energy](/Helmholtz_free_energy)
A thermodynamic potential, defined as the internal energy minus the product of temperature and entropy. It represents the maximum amount of work that a thermodynamic system can perform at constant temperature and volume.

[hertz](/Hertz) (Hz)
The SI unit of frequency, defined as one cycle per second.

[Higgs boson](/Higgs_boson)
An elementary particle in the Standard Model of particle physics that is associated with the Higgs field, which permeates space and gives mass to other fundamental particles.

[homeokinetics](/Homeokinetics)
The physics of complex, self-organizing systems.

[horsepower](/Horsepower) (hp)
A unit of power, historically used for engines. One horsepower is approximately 746 watts.

[Huygens–Fresnel principle](/Huygens%E2%80%93Fresnel_principle)
A principle that explains wave propagation by considering each point on a wavefront as a source of secondary spherical wavelets.

[hydrostatics](/Hydrostatics)
The branch of [fluid mechanics](/Fluid_mechanics) that studies fluids at rest, including concepts like pressure and buoyancy.

---

## I

[ice point](/Ice_point)
The temperature at which ice melts or water freezes at standard atmospheric pressure (0°C or 32°F).

[impedance](/Electrical_impedance)
The total opposition that a circuit presents to alternating current, combining resistance and reactance. Measured in [ohms](/Ohm).

[implosion](/Implosion_(mechanical_process))
A process in which an object collapses or breaks inward due to external pressure being greater than internal pressure.

[impulse](/Impulse_(physics))
The change in momentum of an object, equal to the product of the average force acting on it and the time interval over which it acts.

[indefinite integral](/Indefinite_integral)
The antiderivative of a function, representing a family of functions differing by a constant.

[inductance](/Inductance)
The property of an electrical conductor or circuit element to oppose a change in the electric current flowing through it, by storing energy in a magnetic field. Measured in [henries](/Henry_(unit)).

[infrasound](/Infrasound)
Sound waves with frequencies below the lower limit of human audibility, typically below 20 Hz.

[inertia](/Inertia)
The resistance of any physical object to any change in its state of motion; its tendency to remain at rest or in uniform motion in a straight line. It's quantified by mass.

[inductive reactance](/Electrical_reactance)
The opposition offered by an inductor to the flow of alternating current, which is directly proportional to the frequency and inductance.

[integral](/Integral)
A fundamental concept in calculus representing the area under a curve or the accumulation of quantities.

[integral transform](/Integral_transform)
A mathematical operation that converts a function from one domain to another, often simplifying analysis. Examples include the Laplace and Fourier transforms.

[International System of Units](/International_System_of_Units) (SI)
The modern, standard system of measurement, based on seven base units (meter, kilogram, second, ampere, kelvin, mole, candela) and a decimal system of prefixes.

[invariant mass](/Invariant_mass)
In particle physics, a quantity that is the same for all observers, regardless of their frame of reference. It's related to the rest mass of a particle.

[ion](/Ion)
An atom or molecule that has gained or lost one or more electrons, resulting in a net electric charge.

[ionic bond](/Ionic_bond)
A chemical bond formed by the electrostatic attraction between oppositely charged ions.

[ionization](/Ionization)
The process of converting an atom or molecule into an ion by adding or removing charged particles, typically electrons.

[ionization chamber](/Ionization_chamber)
A type of radiation detector that measures ionizing radiation by detecting the ions produced when the radiation passes through a gas.

[ionizing radiation](/Ionizing_radiation)
Radiation with enough energy to remove electrons from atoms and molecules, such as alpha particles, beta particles, gamma rays, and X-rays.

[isotope](/Isotope)
Atoms of the same element that have different numbers of neutrons in their nucleus. They have the same atomic number but different mass numbers.

---

## J

[Josephson effect](/Josephson_effect)
A quantum mechanical phenomenon occurring in superconductors, where a supercurrent can flow across a thin insulating barrier between two superconductors.

[joule](/Joule) (J)
The SI derived unit of energy, work, or heat. It is defined as the work done when a force of one newton displaces an object by one meter.

[jerk](/Jerk_(physics))
The rate of change of acceleration; the third derivative of displacement with respect to time. It describes how quickly acceleration changes.

---

## K

[Kelvin](/Kelvin) (K)
The SI base unit of thermodynamic temperature. It is defined such that absolute zero is 0 K.

[kinematics](/Kinematics)
The branch of classical mechanics that describes motion without considering its causes. It focuses on displacement, velocity, and acceleration.

[kinetic energy](/Kinetic_energy)
The energy possessed by an object due to its motion. It is given by the formula KE = ½mv², where m is mass and v is velocity. Contrast with [potential energy](/Potential_energy).

[Kirchhoff's circuit laws](/Kirchhoff%27s_circuit_laws)
Two fundamental laws governing electric circuits: the current law (sum of currents entering a junction is zero) and the voltage law (sum of voltage drops around a closed loop is zero).

[Kirchhoff's equations](/Kirchhoff%27s_equations)
In fluid dynamics, these equations describe the motion of a rigid body within an ideal fluid.

---

## L

[Lagrangian mechanics](/Lagrangian_mechanics)
A reformulation of classical mechanics that uses the Lagrangian function (kinetic energy minus potential energy) to describe the motion of a system.

[laminar flow](/Laminar_flow)
A flow regime characterized by smooth, parallel layers of fluid with no significant mixing between layers. Contrast with [turbulent flow](/Turbulent_flow).

[Laplace transform](/Laplace_transform)
An integral transform used extensively in solving differential equations, particularly in engineering and physics.

[Laplace–Runge–Lenz vector](/Laplace%E2%80%93Runge%E2%80%93Lenz_vector) (LRL vector)
A vector used in celestial mechanics that is conserved for systems with a 1/r² central force, describing the orientation of the orbit.

[laser](/Laser)
A device that emits a highly concentrated, monochromatic, and coherent beam of light through stimulated emission. The acronym stands for "light amplification by stimulated emission of radiation."

[law of universal gravitation](/Newton%27s_law_of_universal_gravitation)
See [Newton's law of universal gravitation](/Newton%27s_law_of_universal_gravitation).

[LC circuit](/LC_circuit)
An electrical circuit consisting of an [inductor](/Inductor) (L) and a [capacitor](/Capacitor) (C), used in resonant circuits and filters.

[Lenz's law](/Lenz%27s_law)
A law stating that the direction of an induced current in a conductor due to electromagnetic induction is such that it opposes the change in magnetic flux that produced it.

[lepton](/Lepton)
A type of elementary particle that does not interact via the strong force. Electrons and neutrinos are examples of leptons.

[lever](/Lever)
A simple machine consisting of a rigid rod pivoted at a fixed point (fulcrum), used to multiply force or change its direction.

[levitation](/Levitation_(physics))
The phenomenon of suspending an object in the air by means of magnetic or acoustic forces.

[light](/Light)
Electromagnetic radiation within the range of wavelengths visible to the human eye. More broadly, it encompasses all electromagnetic radiation.

[linear actuator](/Linear_actuator)
A device that produces motion in a straight line.

[linear algebra](/Linear_algebra)
The branch of mathematics dealing with vector spaces, linear mappings, and systems of linear equations.

[line of force](/Line_of_force)
A curve drawn in a force field such that its tangent at any point gives the direction of the force at that point.

[linear elasticity](/Linear_elasticity)
A simplified model of material behavior where stress is directly proportional to strain, and the material returns to its original shape upon removal of the load.

[Liouville's theorem](/Liouville%27s_theorem_(conformal_mappings))
A theorem in classical mechanics stating that the volume occupied by a system of particles in phase space is conserved over time.

[liquid](/Liquid)
A state of matter with a definite volume but no fixed shape, taking the form of its container.

[liquid crystal](/Liquid_crystal) (LC)
A state of matter with properties between those of a conventional liquid and a solid crystal, exhibiting ordered molecular arrangement.

[longitudinal wave](/Longitudinal_wave)
A wave in which the particles of the medium vibrate parallel to the direction of wave propagation, such as sound waves.

---

## M

[M-theory](/M-theory)
A proposed unified theory in [string theory](/String_theory) that encompasses five different superstring theories and 11-dimensional supergravity.

[Mach number](/Mach_number)
A dimensionless quantity representing the ratio of the speed of an object or fluid flow to the [speed of sound](/Speed_of_sound) in the surrounding medium.

[Mach's principle](/Mach%27s_principle)
A concept suggesting that an object's inertia is determined by its interaction with all the matter in the universe.

[machine](/Machine)
A device that uses mechanical power to perform some task. It typically involves multiple parts working together.

[machine element](/Machine_element)
A basic component of a machine, such as a gear, lever, or bearing.

[Maclaurin series](/Maclaurin_series)
A specific case of the Taylor series, representing a function as an infinite sum of terms calculated from the function's derivatives at a single point (the origin).

[magnetic field](/Magnetic_field)
A vector field that describes the magnetic influence of electric currents and magnetic materials. It exerts forces on moving electric charges and magnetic dipoles.

[magnetism](/Magnetism)
A physical phenomenon produced by moving electric charges and electric currents, associated with magnetic fields.

[magnetostatics](/Magnetostatics)
The study of magnetic fields that are constant in time, typically produced by permanent magnets or steady electric currents.

[mass](/Mass)
A fundamental property of matter, representing its resistance to acceleration ([inertia](/Inertia)) and the strength of its gravitational attraction.

[mass balance](/Mass_balance)
An accounting of all the mass entering, leaving, and accumulating within a system, based on the law of conservation of mass.

mass density
See [density](/Density).

[mass flux](/Mass_flux)
The rate of mass flow per unit area.

[mass moment of inertia](/Mass_moment_of_inertia)
The rotational analogue of mass, measuring an object's resistance to changes in its rotational motion.

[mass number](/Mass_number)
The total number of protons and neutrons (nucleons) in an atomic nucleus.

[mass spectrometry](/Mass_spectrometry)
An analytical technique used to measure the mass-to-charge ratio of ions, allowing for the identification and quantification of chemical substances.

[material properties](/Material_properties)
The characteristics of a material that describe its behavior under various physical conditions, such as strength, elasticity, and conductivity.

[materials science](/Materials_science)
An interdisciplinary field that studies the properties, structure, and applications of materials, often focusing on solids.

[mathematical physics](/Mathematical_physics)
The application of advanced mathematical methods to problems in physics and the development of new mathematical techniques for physical theories.

[mathematics](/Mathematics)
The abstract study of quantity, structure, space, change, and related concepts.

[matrix](/Matrix_(mathematics))
A rectangular array of numbers or symbols, used extensively in linear algebra and various areas of physics.

[matter](/Matter)
Anything that has [mass](/Mass) and occupies space. It is composed of fundamental particles.

[Maxwell's equations](/Maxwell%27s_equations)
A set of fundamental equations that describe the behavior of electric and magnetic fields and their interactions with charges and currents. They form the basis of classical electrodynamics.

[measure of central tendency](/Measure_of_central_tendency)
A statistical value that represents the center or typical value of a dataset, such as the mean, median, or mode.

[mechanical energy](/Mechanical_energy)
The sum of the kinetic and potential energy of an object.

[mechanical filter](/Mechanical_filter)
A device that selectively transmits or blocks mechanical vibrations or waves.

[mechanical equilibrium](/Mechanical_equilibrium)
A state where the net force and net torque on an object are zero, resulting in no change in its state of motion.

[mechanical wave](/Mechanical_wave)
A wave that requires a medium (solid, liquid, or gas) to propagate, such as sound waves.

[mechanics](/Mechanics)
The branch of [physics](/Physics) that studies the motion of objects and the forces that affect motion.

[melting](/Melting)
Also known as fusion, this is the phase transition of a substance from a solid to a liquid state, occurring at its melting point.

[meson](/Meson)
A type of hadron composed of a quark and an antiquark. Mesons are typically unstable particles.

[modulus of elasticity](/Modulus_of_elasticity)
See [elastic modulus](/Elastic_modulus).

[molar concentration](/Molar_concentration)
The amount of a substance in moles per unit volume of solution.

[molar mass](/Molar_mass)
The mass of one mole of a substance, expressed in grams per mole (g/mol).

[molecule](/Molecule)
A group of two or more atoms held together by chemical bonds.

[molecular physics](/Molecular_physics)
The branch of [physics](/Physics) that studies the physical properties and behavior of molecules.

[moment](/Moment_(physics))
In physics, a measure of the tendency of a force or mass distribution to cause rotation about an axis.

[moment of inertia](/Moment_of_inertia)
The rotational analogue of mass, quantifying an object's resistance to angular acceleration.

[momentum](/Momentum)
A vector quantity defined as the product of an object's mass and its velocity. It represents the "quantity of motion."

[monochromatic light](/Spectral_color)
Light of a single wavelength or a very narrow range of wavelengths.

[motion](/Motion_(physics))
Any change in the position of an object over time. Described by concepts like velocity and acceleration.

[muon](/Muon)
An elementary particle, a type of lepton, similar to the electron but much more massive and unstable.

